data.content:
Here's what breaks in EF Core 10 and the fixes:

---

## 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — expression tree no longer compiles

**Breaking change:** `ExecuteUpdateAsync` now accepts a regular `Func<…>` instead of `Expression<Func<…>>`. Your manual expression-tree code won't compile.

**Fix — dramatically simpler:**
```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

---

## 2. Complex type columns — name collisions & nested paths

Two changes:

| Change | Effect |
|--------|--------|
| Column uniquification | `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` no longer silently share one column — a numeric suffix is appended. |
| Nested full-path naming | `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` now maps to `Payment_BillingAddress_City` instead of `BillingAddress_City`. |

**Fix — pin explicit column names to preserve your existing schema:**
```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street"));
});

// For nested complex types, keep old names:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

Or, if both columns *should* share a column (rare), use the same `HasColumnName` value for both.

---

## 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

**Breaking change:** All methods (`CommandReaderExecuting`, `CommandReaderExecuted`, etc.) now require an additional `string logCommandText` parameter (contains redacted SQL for logging).

**Fix:**
```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← add this
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (sensitive data redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual execution SQL
    }
}
```

---

**Summary:** The biggest win is #1 — you can delete all that expression-tree plumbing. The other two are signature/schema fixes that just need updating to match the new conventions.
